        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-09-25T18:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-09-25T18:00:00-05:00" n="873"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d873">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">818.51/884: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Minister in Costa Rica</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Hornibrook</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-09-25T19:00:00-04:00"
                            >September 25, 1940—7 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>97. Your 118, September 25, 10 a.m.<note n="1" xml:id="d873fn1">Not
                        printed.</note> Following press release was given out last night by Federal
                    Loan Agency.</p>
                <quote rend="blockquote">
                    <p>“Jesse Jones, Federal Loan Administrator, announced today the Export-Import
                        Bank has authorized a loan to the Government of Costa Rica of 4,600,000
                        dollars for the construction of a section of the Pan American highway
                        extending from San José to the Panama border, where it will connect with the
                        Panamanian road south to the Canal.</p>
                    <p>“The loan will be at 4 per cent interest, maturing over a period of 10 years
                        and will be guaranteed by the National Bank of Costa Rica and repaid from
                        the proceeds of the gasoline tax. Approximately 60 per cent of the proceeds
                        of the loan will be used for the purchase of equipment in the United
                        States.</p>
                    <p>“It will require approximately 4 years to complete the road, and its
                        construction will be especially helpful to Costa Rica in meeting its
                        unemployment situation due to drastic curtailment of its coffee export
                        market. The United States Public Roads Administration will lend the Costa
                        Rican Government engineers to supervise and assist in the construction of
                        the road.</p>
                    <p>“The loan was negotiated by Dr. Luis Anderson of Costa Rica, assisted by
                        Señor Pena, President of the National Bank of Costa Rica, and Señor
                        Matamoros, technical adviser.”</p>
                </quote>
                <p>Please forward by air mail any press comment on this loan.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
